A tsunami spawned by a 7.0 magnitude earthquake crashed into Papua New Guinea's north coast, crushing villages and killing nearly 600 people, officials said Sunday.
Australia will provide transport for relief supplies and a mobile hospital to Papua New Guinea (PNG) following Friday's tsunami tragedy.
Sixteen people were confirmed dead in the devastated Arop village, and two children had died in Malol, which was wiped out.
The 23-foot (seven-meter) wall of water hit Friday night without warning following an earthquake about 12 miles (30 kilometers) off the coast of Papua New Guinea in the Pacific Ocean.
